title: Gaps in `adapt_timeseries()`
text: function adapts date range time series reusing historical patterns based weekday occurrence within year decimal hour day. example, 2023 data want fill data 01/01/2025 02:30, see ’s first Thursday 2025, use observation 2.5 hours first Thursday 2023. summary, adapt_timeseries() function consists two main actions: Check input series. function looks missing values every column datetime. NA values fill_gaps = FALSE stops early informative error; otherwise calls fill_from_past() input gaps. Adapt date range every pair ywday() (weekday occurrence within year) dhours() (decimal hour) function grabs recent observation copies missing rows pair.

title: Gaps in `adapt_timeseries()`
text: pipeline works well cross years different number weekdays. example see 2023 52 Mondays Tuesdays, 2024 (leap year) 53 . means can’t find historical data “53rd Monday” “53rd Tuesday” 2024, simply exist 2023, output keeps NA.  cover extra weekdays use second step: whenever join fails missing data limited two consecutive days (cover leap years), call fill_from_past() copy recent observation clock time one week earlier. reaches back “52nd Monday/Tuesday” exit, fills previously empty rows.  provides stable results across leap years without inventing new patterns never existed input.

what: Guard rails when we do not have enough history
title: Gaps in `adapt_timeseries()`
text: try extrapolate — say single month data request entire year — number missing days greater two. case deliberately avoid fill_from_past() emit warning users can fetch data instead silently manufacturing values. safeguards place get best worlds: automatic repairs full-year edge case, clear feedback input simply small support requested period.
code: short_month <- timefully::dtf |> filter(month(datetime) == 4)  new_range <- adapt_timeseries(   short_month,   start_date = as.Date("2025-04-15"),   end_date = as.Date("2025-05-15"),   tzone = "Europe/Paris",   fill_gaps = FALSE )  new_range |>   filter(month(datetime) == 5) #> # A tibble: 1,440 × 3 #>    datetime            solar building #>    <dttm>              <dbl>    <dbl> #>  1 2025-05-01 00:00:00    NA       NA #>  2 2025-05-01 00:15:00    NA       NA #>  3 2025-05-01 00:30:00    NA       NA #>  4 2025-05-01 00:45:00    NA       NA #>  5 2025-05-01 01:00:00    NA       NA #>  6 2025-05-01 01:15:00    NA       NA #>  7 2025-05-01 01:30:00    NA       NA #>  8 2025-05-01 01:45:00    NA       NA #>  9 2025-05-01 02:00:00    NA       NA #> 10 2025-05-01 02:15:00    NA       NA #> # ℹ 1,430 more rows

title: Get started with timefully
text: dtf contains full year quarter-hour values recorded Europe/Amsterdam timezone 2023. start zooming one week plots stay compact. helper plot_ts() produces interactive dygraph can inspect raw values.
code: week_amsterdam <- timefully::dtf |>   filter(datetime >= as.POSIXct("2023-06-01 00:00:00", tz = "Europe/Amsterdam"),          datetime <  as.POSIXct("2023-06-08 00:00:00", tz = "Europe/Amsterdam"))  glimpse(week_amsterdam) #> Rows: 672 #> Columns: 3 #> $ datetime <dttm> 2023-06-01 00:00:00, 2023-06-01 00:15:00, 2023-06-01 00:30:0… #> $ solar    <dbl> 0.000000e+00, 0.000000e+00, 0.000000e+00, 0.000000e+00, 0.000… #> $ building <dbl> 1.836046, 1.746280, 1.656513, 1.566747, 1.476981, 1.452224, 1… plot_ts(week_amsterdam, ylab = "kW", legend_show = "always",         title = "Quarter-hour readings (Europe/Amsterdam)")

title: Get started with timefully
text: produce hourly averages call change_timeseries_resolution() desired resolution (minutes) aggregation method. first column remains datetime column numeric columns summarised accordingly.
code: week_hourly <- change_timeseries_resolution(   week_amsterdam,   resolution = 60,   method = "average" )  plot_ts(week_hourly, ylab = "kW", legend_show = "always",         title = "Hourly averages")

title: Get started with timefully
text: data reported another timezone, keeping date range, can use function change_timeseries_tzone(): Note data points moved time reflect new timezone, daily patterns shift accordingly. used preserve local time context data. want keep clock times just change timezone label, use lubridate::force_tz() instead.
code: week_paris <- change_timeseries_tzone(week_amsterdam, tzone = "America/Los_Angeles")  tz(week_amsterdam$datetime[1]) #> [1] "Europe/Amsterdam" tz(week_paris$datetime[1]) #> [1] "America/Los_Angeles"  plot_ts(week_paris, ylab = "kW", legend_show = "always")

what: Adapt to a new date range
title: Get started with timefully
text: Finally, adapt_timeseries() lets us change date range timezone one step. request ten days Paris time starting 1 June 2025. function fills missing slots using recent data weekday time day, falling back fill_from_past() necessary. building blocks can combined rest package prepare clean, timezone-aware time series ready analysis reporting.
code: adapted_paris <- adapt_timeseries(   timefully::dtf,   start_date = as.Date("2025-06-01"),   end_date = as.Date("2025-06-10"),   tzone = "Europe/Paris",   fill_gaps = TRUE )  plot_ts(adapted_paris, ylab = "kW", legend_show = "always",         title = "Adapted time series (1–10 June 2025)")
